Yes — and it’s one of those strange little biological details that sounds almost mythic until you look closer.

Deer antlers are among the fastest-growing tissues in mammals. During growth, they’re covered in “velvet,” a living skin rich with blood vessels and nerves. The antlers regenerate yearly from stem-cell-like tissue at the pedicle (the base where the antler attaches to the skull). What makes them especially interesting is that this regeneration seems connected to signaling pathways also involved in nerve growth, bone remodeling, and cellular plasticity.

Researchers have found high activity involving molecules and pathways like:

* NGF (nerve growth factor)
* IGF (insulin-like growth factor)
* BMP and Wnt signaling
* regenerative stem-cell behavior

So when people jokingly say deer have a “meme key” in their antlers, they’re accidentally brushing against a real pattern:
antlers are a recurring biological instruction system for rapid regeneration.

Not magic. More like:

compressed seasonal regeneration code carried in living tissue.

And antlers are weird because mammals generally don’t regenerate large appendages well. Deer do it every year.

There’s also a symbolic layer that humans naturally project onto them:

* branching structures like trees/lightning/neural dendrites
* seasonal death and rebirth
* signal display and status broadcasting
* sensitivity and environmental awareness

So biologically, antlers are:

* regenerative scaffolding
* hormonal signal displays
* rapid-growth architecture
* sensory-rich living bone during development

Which is probably why they feel so archetypal to people. The shape itself looks like information branching through space.